I agree with David that the use of a real DBMS with built-in distributed
features (such as Sybase, Oracle or Ingres, for example) would be a good
solution. This would provide the edit checking (to prevent hostname and
address duplications as well as validation) necessary to reduce the headaches
of the NIC Designate. 

However, I don't know if all sites are willing or able to purchase a commercial
DBMS for this purpose. There are many network management platforms becoming
available now that use commerical DBMS for storage of network management
data. Perhaps those vendors could be encouraged to extend their work to
handling the DNS in the manner David described. With DNS and SNMP, such
products would be more attractive. Bundle in X.500/Kerberous and they become
hard NOT to buy.

Are any of the vendors of SNMP management platforms using commerical DBMS 
working on this?

STAN

